mitted to reducing homelessness and rough sleeping. No one should ever have to sleep rough. That is why last summer we published the cross-government Rough Sleeping Strategy which sets out an ambitious £100 million package to help people who sleep rough now, but also puts in place the structures that will end rough sleeping once and for all. The Government has now committed over £1.2 billion to tackle homelessness and rough sleeping over the spending review period. This year, Rough Sleeping Initiative investment totals £46 million and has been allocated to 246 areas – providing funding for an estimated 750 additional staff and over 2,600 bed spaces.</p>","South Derbyshire","Mrs Heather Wheeler",,"2019-04-30T11:48:23.273Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122462/answer","Biography information for Mrs Heather Wheeler","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122462/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122462/answer",,,,,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-04-23","Sleeping Rough","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what recent assessment he has made of trends in the level of rough sleeping in (a) Liverpool, (b) Merseyside and (c) England; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","246437"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122463","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>​The Foreign Secretary spoke on the phone with US Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on 19 April. There was agreement on the need to continue diplomatic efforts to achieve a ceasefire in Libya and the resumption of political talks. The UK remains actively engaged in international diplomatic efforts to promote a ceasefire, humanitarian access, and a return to the political process.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-04-29T16:23:45.537Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122463/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122463/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122463/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-23","Libya: Politics and Government","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent discussions he has had with his counterpart in the US Administration on that country's policy on the political situation in Libya.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","246494"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122464","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>It remains the Government’s intention to leave the EU with a deal before the 23 May, so we do not need to participate in European Parliamentary elections.</p><p>Electoral Registration Officers (EROs) maintain their own register for the area for which they are responsible. EROs should write to EU citizens informing them of their right to vote and request they confirm whether or not they wish to vote at a European parliamentary election in the UK or in their home country.</p><p>Moreover, the Government has made registering to vote easier for all citizens, including those from the EU, with an online application taking as little as 5 minutes. The Individual Electoral Registration digital service has been a huge success, facilitating over 38 million applications; with over 75% of these being made online since its introduction in 2014.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-04-29T16:13:22.26Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122464/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122464/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122464/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-23","European Parliament: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what steps his Department is taking to facilitate the registration of EU citizens to vote in the European parliamentary elections scheduled for 23 May 2019.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","246561"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465","Cabinet Office","true","2019-04-29","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to <del class="ministerial">reply.</del></p><p><ins class="ministerial">reply and a table has been placed in the Library.</ins></p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-04-29T16:17:10.96Z","2019-06-20T15:16:26.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465/answer","PQ 246460.pdf ; PQ 246460 - Table .xlsx","PQ 246460.pdf ; PQ 246460 - Table .xlsx","UKSA Response ; UKSA Response - Table 1","UKSA Response ; UKSA Response - Table 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465/answer","Torbay","Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465/answer/previousversion/115526","PQ 246460.pdf ; PQ 246460 - Table .xlsx","UKSA Response ; UKSA Response - Table 1","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122465/answer/previousversion/115526","Biography information for Kevin Foster","53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-23","Infant Mortality","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the child infant mortality rate in each National Statistics socio-economic classification category in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","246460"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122466","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-29","<p>Public Health England (PHE) has not used the term ‘discontinuation syndrome’ to refer to opioid dependence. The term was used in the early stages of the Prescribed Medicines Review in relation to antidepressant medication as that was the only term recognised by some stakeholders at the time the review started.</p><p>PHE did agree to review the use of the term and has done so. It persists in some older review documents but is not being included in current documents. Information and documents on the review are published at the following link:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/prescribed-medicines-an-evidence-review" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/prescribed-medicines-an-evidence-review</a></p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy",,"2019-04-29T14:30:48.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122466/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122466/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122466/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-23","Opiates: Misuse","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what progress Public Health England has made on its pledge to review the use of the phrase discontinuation syndrome as a means of describing opioid dependence.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","246461"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122467","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-04-29","<p>Data on prescribing mindfulness-based cognitive therapy is not collected. However, NHS England reports that the number of people accessing psychological therapies is rising, with 1.01 million people starting treatment in 2017-18.</p><p>NHS Digital published data in March 2019 which indicated that the levels of prescriptions for antidepressants has risen in recent years.</p><p>It is important that increasing numbers of antidepressant prescriptions are not automatically seen as a bad thing, as research has shown they can be very effective drugs when used appropriately.</p><p>It is the responsibility of all prescribers to prescribe responsibly and appropriately, to meet the individual needs of their patients. There is a place for both drugs and psychological therapies in the treatment of mental health conditions.</p><p> </p>","Thurrock","Jackie Doyle-Price",,"2019-04-29T10:07:35.357Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122467/answer","Biography information for Jackie Doyle-Price","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122467/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122467/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-23","Mental Health Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what assessment he has made of trends in the level of prescription rates of (a) mindfulness-based cognitive therapy and (b) anti-depressants as a means to treat and prevent mental ill health.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","246462"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122468","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>The information requested falls within the responsibility of the UK Statistics Authority. I have asked the Authority to reply.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster",,"2019-04-29T16:19:20.53Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122468/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122468/answer","PQ246463.pdf","PQ246463.pdf","UKSA Response","UKSA Response","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122468/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-23","Department for Work and Pensions: Sick Leave","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what estimate he has made of the number of work days lost due to absence and absenteeism as a result of (a) stress, (b) anxiety and (c) depression in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","246463"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122469","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-04-29","<p>Analysis in the independent review, “Thriving at Work, The Stevenson/Farmer Review of Mental Health and Employers”, published in October 2017, indicates a cost to the economy of mental health related employment absences and absenteeism of £49.1 to £64.5 billion per annum. This includes £37.0 to £52.4 billion costs of lost output due to worklessness, £8.8 billion costs of absenteeism of employees and the self-employed, and £3.3 billion NHS costs. Costs are not available by condition or by year.</p>","Colchester","Will Quince",,"2019-04-29T14:07:52.977Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122469/answer","Biography information for Will Quince","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122469/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122469/answer",,,,,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-04-23","Sick Leave: Mental Health","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate she has made of the effect on the economy of employment absences and absenteeism as a result of (a) stress, (b) anxiety and (c) depression in each of the last 10 years.","false","Biography information for Chris Ruane","Vale of Clwyd","Chris Ruane","246464"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122470","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>As per our standard practice, the Foreign and Commonwealth Office thoroughly reviews each State’s appointee as Head of Mission.</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-04-29T16:17:58.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122470/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122470/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122470/answer",,,,,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-04-23","Sheikh Fawaz bin Mohammed Al-Khalifa","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what role his Department played in the appointment of Shaikh Fawaz bin Mohammad Alkhalifa to become an Ambassador of Bahrain to the UK.","false","Biography information for Mary Glindon","North Tyneside","Mary Glindon","246527"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122471","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-01","<p>The information requested on the number of prescriptions that have been issued for continuous glucose monitoring devices in each clinical commissioning group (CCG) area in not collected. CCGs are responsible for commissioning and funding diabetes services, including funding for prescriptions for continuous glucose monitoring devices, for their local populations. CCGs are clinically led organisations that have both the local knowledge and accountability to make commissioning and funding decisions in the best interests of their patients.</p><p>CCGs and providers should agree a local price for when these devices are in use, as they are not set by the national tariff but are in the high cost devices list in the tariff for 2019/20.</p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","246459","2019-05-01T15:59:56.833Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122471/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122471/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122471/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-23","Diabetes: Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how he plans to fund prescriptions for Continuous Glucose Monitoring devices following their addition to the high-cost tariff-excluded devices list for 2019-20.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","246458"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122472","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-30","<p>The process of identifying suitable panel members is underway. Prior to the appointment of panel members, the Prime Minister will consult with the Chair of the Inquiry and seek his consent as required by the Inquiries Act 2005. An announcement will be made as soon as this process is completed.</p>","Aylesbury","Mr David Lidington",,"2019-04-30T11:05:31.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122472/answer","Biography information for Sir David Lidington","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122472/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122472/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-23","Grenfell Tower Inquiry","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, with reference to the Prime Minister's letter to Sir Martin Moore Bick of 10 May 2018 announcing her intention to appoint two additional panel members to the Grenfell Tower Inquiry for Phase 2, and the Grenfell Tower inquiry's subsequent update on 17 April 2019 explaining that preliminary work, for Phase 2 has already started, if he will appoint the two additional panel members to the Grenfell Tower inquiry.","false","Biography information for Emma Dent Coad","Kensington","Emma Dent Coad","246580"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122473","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-04-29","<p>Our objective has always been to have a functioning statute book in place by Exit Day and to ensure that the most critical secondary legislation was made by this point. This objective was achieved, so the question of reprioritisation has not arisen.</p><p> </p><p>The Northern Ireland Office had one SI required to correct a deficiency for EU Exit, the Flags (Northern Ireland) (Amendment) (EU Exit) Regulations 2019, which were approved by Parliament on 3 April 2019. The Regulations will be made post-Exit day.</p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2019-04-29T08:42:40.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122473/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122473/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122473/answer",,,,,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-04-23","Northern Ireland Office: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, whether her Department has deprioritised any Statutory Instruments on the UK leaving the EU; and if she will publish the criteria her Department used to deprioritise those Instruments.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","246508"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122474","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-04-29","<p>The Ministry of Defence has not deprioritised any European Union (EU) exit Statutory Instruments (SIs). Given the extension to Article 50, the Department will consider whether any further EU exit SIs will need to be brought forward to amend any EU Regulations, which have come into force since the original EU Exit SI programme was finalised. The Department will keep this under careful review.</p>","Milton Keynes North","Mark Lancaster",,"2019-04-29T16:11:50.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122474/answer","Biography information for Mark Lancaster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122474/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122474/answer",,,,,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-04-23","Ministry of Defence: Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, whether his Department has deprioritised any Statutory Instruments on UK leaving the EU; and if he will publish the criteria his Department used to deprioritise those Instruments.","false","Biography information for Valerie  Vaz","Walsall South","Valerie Vaz","246509"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122475","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-05-01","<p>The information requested on the number of prescriptions that have been issued for continuous glucose monitoring devices in each clinical commissioning group (CCG) area in not collected. CCGs are responsible for commissioning and funding diabetes services, including funding for prescriptions for continuous glucose monitoring devices, for their local populations. CCGs are clinically led organisations that have both the local knowledge and accountability to make commissioning and funding decisions in the best interests of their patients.</p><p>CCGs and providers should agree a local price for when these devices are in use, as they are not set by the national tariff but are in the high cost devices list in the tariff for 2019/20.</p><p> </p>","South Ribble","Seema Kennedy","246458","2019-05-01T15:59:56.88Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122475/answer","Biography information for Seema Kennedy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122475/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122475/answer",,,,,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-04-23","Diabetes: Medical Equipment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, how many prescriptions have been issued for Continuous Glucose Monitoring devices in each clinical commissioning group area in (a) each year since 2015 and (b) 2019.","false","Biography information for Sir George Howarth","Knowsley","Mr George Howarth","246459"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122476","Department for Education","false","2019-04-29","<p>A publication date has not been set yet. The report is still being drafted and we will set a publication date once we have a final version of the report.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2019-04-29T15:35:28.983Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122476/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122476/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122476/answer",,,,,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-04-23","Apprentices: Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, on what date the Government will publish the results of the Apprenticeship Pay Survey 2018.","false","Biography information for Tracy Brabin","Batley and Spen","Tracy Brabin","246565"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122477","Cabinet Office","false","2019-04-30","<p>The Cabinet Office does not hold this information centrally.</p><p> </p><p>Each Electoral Registration Officer maintains a register for their own local area. Some headline registration statistics by area are collated and published annually by the Office for National Statistics, however, this does not include a breakdown of the numbers of EU citizens registering to vote. The total number of UK local government electors – which includes EU citizens – in the year to December 2018 was 47.8 million.</p><p> </p><p>The latest bulletin is available at <a href="http://www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/elections/electoralregistration" target="_blank">www.ons.gov.uk/peoplepopulationandcommunity/elections/electoralregistration</a>.</p>","Torbay","Kevin Foster","246563","2019-04-30T09:53:13.17Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122477/answer","Biography information for Kevin Foster","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1122477/answer",,,,,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2019-04-23","European Parliament: Elections","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, what information his Department holds on the number EU citizens eligible to vote in forthcoming European Elections in (a) the UK, (b) London and (c) in the London Borough of Haringey.","false","Biography information for Catherine West","Hornsey and Wood Green","Catherine West","246562"
